<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="ch5-section-expanding-acceleration-subsection-k-hat" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Expanding the total derivative of <m>\hat{k}</m></title>

    <p>
        Again using the definition of the total derivative:
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-k-full" number="yes">
            \frac{D \hat{k}}{Dt}
            =
            \frac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial t}
            + u \, \frac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial x}
            + v \, \frac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial y}
            + w \, \frac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial z}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Again, the first term on the right-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-k-full" text="type-global" /> is
    </p>
    
    <p>
        <md>
            \frac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial t} = \vec{0}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        since,
        at a fixed location on Earth or in its atmosphere,
        the local orientation of a unit direction vector does not change with time.
        Specifically,
        <m>\hat{k}</m> always points locally upward.
    </p>

    <p>
        Furthermore,
        <xref ref="ch5-local-cartesian-coordinates-sphericity" text="type-global" />
        reveals that
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            \frac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial z} = \vec{0}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Therefore, <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-k-full" text="type-global" /> reduces to
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-k-reduced" number="yes"> 
            \frac{D \hat{k}}{Dt}
            =
            u \, \frac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial x}
            + v \, \frac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial y}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        To evaluate <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{k}}{\partial x}</m>,
        we again make a horizontal slice perpendicular to Earth's axis of rotation at latitude <m>\phi</m>
        to create a disk of radius <m>a \cos{\phi}</m>.
        As shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-k-x-start" text="type-global" /> below,
        we then consider the difference in <m>\hat{k}</m>'s orientation
        when its anchoring point is placed at two nearby points on Earth's surface with latitude <m>\phi</m>
        and longitudes separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m> along arc <m>\delta x</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-k-x-start">
        <caption>
            North polar projection showing portions of unit direction vectors
            <m>\hat{k}_1 \, \cos{\phi}</m> and <m>\hat{k}_2 \, \cos{\phi}</m>
            placed on Earth's surface at two nearby points at the edge of the disk of radius <m>a \cos{\phi}</m>
            and separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m> and arc <m>\delta x</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch5-spherical-k-x-start.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                Two portions of unit direction vectors at two nearby points
                on the edge of a circular disk viewed from above.
                The vectors point outward away from the center of the disk.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Before going further,
        note <m>\hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}</m> rather than <m>\hat{k}</m> is shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-k-x-start" text="type-global" />
        because <m>\hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}</m> is the projection of <m>\hat{k}</m> onto the disk,
        as shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-k-x-breakdown" text="type-global" /> below.
        The remaining portion of <m>\hat{k}</m>,
        <m>\hat{k} \, \sin{\phi}</m>,
        does not change with <m>x</m>,
        as it always points vertically upward from the disk.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-k-x-breakdown">
        <caption>
            Equatorial projection showing the unit direction vectors <m>\hat{i}</m>, <m>\hat{j}</m>, and <m>\hat{k}</m>
            of the local Cartesian coordinate system fixed to Earth's surface at radius <m>a \cos{\phi}</m>
            perpendicular to Earth's axis of rotation,
            where <m>a</m> is Earth's mean radius and <m>\phi</m> is latitude.
            The portion of <m>\hat{k}</m> that points outward perpendicular to Earth's axis of rotation
            is given by <m>\hat{k} \, \cos{\phi}</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch5-spherical-k-x-breakdown.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                A point on Earth's surface with the local Cartesian coordinate system
                as well as a vector projection pointing outward perpendicular to Earth's axis of rotation
                placed at that point.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

</subsection>